<section>
  <p class="eyebrow">Speaker A · exact canon excerpt</p>
  <h2>Article Five</h2>
  <blockquote class="reading"><p>There are children¹, invalids¹, and adults². There are dependents, independents, and interdependents</p><p>Adulthood, defined by the capacity to survive physically and socially without direct intervention of parents or guardians; claimed by competent³ demonstration of the skills necessary: cooking, first aid, communication, sanitation, skill acquisition, shelter infrastructure maintenance.</p><p>Political Adulthood - the capacity to demonstrate self-sufficient interdependency; claimed by demonstration competencies of the body politic: an original, personal Preamble⁵; a hand-written transcription of these Articles⁴; a portfolio of demonstrated skill sets⁶; and a schedule of intended actions⁷. Twelve such are a Political Circle.</p></blockquote>
  <div class="grid">
    <article class="panel"><h3>Plain orientation</h3><p>Article Five makes adulthood a demonstrated capacity. It asks whether a person can survive, communicate, learn, maintain shelter, practice sanitation, and participate in public responsibility.</p></article>
    <article class="panel"><h3>Central tension</h3><p>Competence standards can protect people from unearned authority, but they can also exclude, shame, or bureaucratize adulthood. The article needs strong accessibility and review boundaries.</p></article>
  </div>
</section>
<section>
  <p class="eyebrow">Speaker B · footnote conversation</p>
  <h2>What the notes keep from collapsing</h2>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ¹ · dependence</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> dependents.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> groups children and invalids by need for support, not by worth. Dependency creates obligation, not contempt.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ² · age</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> once adulthood is claimed, all adults are the same legal age, alive now.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> resists age hierarchy among adults. Once competence is demonstrated, the adult enters the same public present.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ³ · competence</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> the capacity to reliably perform a skill, practice an art, or otherwise contribute meaningfully to survival and conversation</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> defines competence by reliable contribution, not status display.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ⁴ · handwriting</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> Hand-writing is the standard, save for cases of prohibitive neurodivergence.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> makes embodied attention visible while preserving an accessibility exception.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ⁵ · preamble</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> A few sentences that demonstrate a grasp of current political realities.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> requires situated awareness. Political adulthood is not abstract identity; it must understand the present field.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ⁶ · portfolio</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> lineaged by craft masters, doctors, or certifying authorities as appropriate.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> keeps skill claims accountable to witnesses and domains of practice.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ⁷ · schedule</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> Providing points of failure so as to determine character and integrity</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> makes intention testable. Character appears when plans meet constraint.</p></article>
