<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">Handbook seed</p>
  <h2>Chapter section: Adulthood as demonstrated competence</h2>
  <p>Article Five shifts adulthood from mere age to demonstrated survival and social capacity. That does not make dependent people lesser; it makes dependency visible so care and authority are not confused.</p>
  <p>A circle applying this article should maintain a public competence map. The map should show who can cook, treat injury, communicate under stress, keep sanitation, learn new skills, maintain shelter, and teach others.</p>
  <p>Political adulthood adds public commitments: a preamble, transcription, portfolio, and schedule. These are not decoration. They make belief, attention, skill, and intended action visible enough to be tested.</p>
</section>
<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">60–90 second script</p>
  <h2>Short video draft</h2>
  <p><strong>Title:</strong> Adulthood is demonstrated</p>
  <p>Article Five says there are children, invalids, and adults; dependents, independents, and interdependents.</p>
  <p>That sounds hard because it is. The point is not to shame dependence. The point is to stop pretending that age alone proves competence or that status alone deserves authority.</p>
  <p>Adulthood is claimed by demonstrated skills: cooking, first aid, communication, sanitation, learning, shelter maintenance. Political adulthood adds a personal preamble, a handwritten transcription, a skill portfolio, and a schedule of intended actions.</p>
  <p>The standard is not perfection. It is evidence. What can you do? What can you learn? What can you maintain? What do you intend? The Way asks adults to become visible to responsibility.</p>
</section>
